It involves analyzing the source code and making changes to the generated machine code to improve the execution time, memory usage, and other performance metrics. Compiler optimization techniques can be broadly classified into two categories: static and dynamic.
Static optimization techniques are applied during the compilation phase, before the program is executed. These techniques analyze the source code and make changes to the generated machine code to improve performance. Some of the most popular static optimization techniques are:
1. Loop unrolling: This technique involves unrolling the loops in the source code to reduce the number of iterations and improve the execution time. For example, if a loop is executed 10 times, the compiler can unroll the loop and execute the body of the loop 10 times in a row, reducing the number of iterations and improving the execution time.
2. Function inlining: This technique involves replacing a function call with the body of the function to reduce the overhead of function calls. For example, if a function is called multiple times in a program, the compiler can replace the function call with the body of the function, reducing the overhead of function calls and improving the execution time.
3. Dead code elimination: This technique involves removing code that is never executed from the generated machine code to reduce the size of the executable and improve the execution time. For example, if a function is called but never executed, the compiler can remove the function from the generated machine code, reducing the size of the executable and improving the execution time.
4. Constant folding: This technique involves replacing constant expressions with their values to reduce the number of operations and improve the execution time. For example, if a constant expression is used multiple times in a program, the compiler can replace the expression with its value, reducing the number of operations and improving the execution time.
